e records that other histories have relied on for the story of Attica and expands that archive, drawing on oral history and applying Black radical theory in ways that center the intellectual and political goals of the incarcerated people who led the struggle. Packed with little-known insights from the prison movement, the Black Panther Party, and the Black Liberation Army, Tip of the Spear promises to transform our understanding of prisons—not only as sites of race war and class war, of counterinsurgency and genocide, but also as sources of defiant Black life, revolutionary consciousness, and abolitionist possibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American prisonersxCivil rightszNew York (State)zAttica. 0aPrison riotszNew York (State)zAttica. 0aRadicalismzNew York (State)zAttica. 0aRevolutionszNew York (State)zAttica. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520396333?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520396333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520396333/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles